    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "the wizard thing is a bit confusing lol. can u just explain it without the metaphors? specifically about the part where it \"stays durable\" if he gets sick. what actually happens to the legal authority in that case?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A durable power of attorney is simply a legal document that grants your dad the authority to act on your behalf, but with a specific clause that says: \"Even if I lose the ability to understand or make decisions, this authority does not end.\"\n\nIn a standard, non-durable power of attorney, the moment your dad loses capacity (due to illness, dementia, or injury), the document automatically terminates. The legal authority vanishes instantly, and your dad can no longer sign checks, pay bills, or manage assets. You would then have to go through a separate, often difficult and expensive process to appoint a new agent or go through probate court to handle those matters.\n\nWith a durable power of attorney, the \"durable\" part is a specific legal provision that overrides the automatic expiration. It ensures that the authority remains active and valid even after your dad loses the mental capacity to understand the terms of the document. This means your dad can still sign checks, manage his finances, and make decisions for you while he is incapacitated, without needing to go through a separate legal appointment.\n\nThink of it like a contract that includes a \"force majeure\" clause. If the boss (your dad) gets sick and can't work,",
      "source": "target",
