      "content": "Yes, if your dad has a durable power of attorney, you can step in and manage his property and bank accounts directly whenever you need to, provided you are acting within the scope of the authority granted in the document.\n\nHowever, there is a very important distinction to make: you are not automatically the \"legal guardian\" or the \"next of kin\" in the eyes of the law. You are the **agent** (or attorney-in-fact) appointed by your dad. This means you are acting on his behalf, not as his substitute.\n\nTo protect yourself while handling his stuff, you absolutely need to do two things:\n1.  **Review the specific language in the document:** Make sure it explicitly states that you have the authority to manage assets, sign checks, and handle financial transactions.\n2.  **Get a formal \"Letter of Authorization\" or \"Power of Attorney Letter\":** This is the most critical step. Even if the document says you have the power, banks and other institutions often require a separate, signed letter from your dad (or a notarized copy of the document) that specifically lists the powers you are allowed to use. Without this, a bank might freeze your account or refuse to process a",
